  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: 8fbeeb9dfd308426da67b82545b339a0, type: 3}
  m_Name: Mushroom_18_Moonring
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: Assembly-CSharp::Hollowfen.Data.MushroomFieldGuideData
  _id: moonring
  _commonName: Moonring
  _latinName: Amanita virosa
  _edibility: 1
  _edibilityLabel: Deadly
  _description: 'Sable''s seedbook name for the Destroying Angel (Amanita virosa) — pure white, elegant, and among the deadliest mushrooms in the world. The old hand called it Moonring for the pale ring on its stem and the cap that seems to hold moonlight; the science is grimmer: the same liver-destroying amatoxins as the Death Cap.'
  _idFeatures:
  - Entirely pure white — cap, gills, stem, all white
  - White free gills, never pink, never brown
  - A white ring (annulus) on the upper stem — the moonring itself
  - Bulbous sac-like volva at the base, often hidden in soil or moss
  - White spore print
  _habitat: Mycorrhizal with broadleaf trees — birch, beech, oak; mixed woodland edges.
  _season: Mid-summer through autumn
  _lookalikes: Field Mushroom (Agaricus campestris) is EDIBLE but has pink or brown gills, never white, and no volva. The unchanging white gills are the universal warning.
  _notes: 'With the Death Cap, this accounts for nearly all fatal mushroom poisonings in temperate regions. Delayed onset: six to twelve hours of nothing, then violent illness, a false recovery, then liver failure. Treat any all-white gilled mushroom with extreme suspicion. Sable''s seedbook does not teach picking it — it teaches knowing it.'
  _photo: {fileID: 21300000, guid: a74608848eb6942deb4c8b7a8485083b, type: 3}
  _photoCredit: Wikimedia Commons
  _worldPrefab: {fileID: 0}
  _displayNameId: mushroom.moonring.name
  _descriptionId: mushroom.moonring.description
